  "Question": "<p>We know that</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_811\"><math alttext=\"e^{x}=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{x^{n}}{n!},x\\in\\mathbb{R},\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><msup><mi>e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mrow><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u221e</mi></msubsup><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mrow><mo>,</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>\u2208</mo><mi>\u211d</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>which can be written out <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_812\"><math alttext=\"e^{x}=\\frac{x^{0}}{0!}+\\frac{x^{1}}{1!}+\\frac{x^{2}}{2!}+\\cdots,\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msup><mi>e</mi><mi>x</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mrow><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msup><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msup><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u22ef</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>but <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_813\"><math alttext=\"0^{0}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><msup><mn>0</mn><mn>0</mn></msup></semantics></math></span> isn't well defined.</p>",
